= Abstract 
This report details the design and implementation of a web-based course scheduling system developed for COSMC 330 at Roger Williams University. The application enables professors to create events, share them with prospective students, and view the aggregated availability. The system was built as a full stack web application and covers the complete software development lifecycle from requirements through deployment.

= Executive Summary
This report covers the Class Planner application built by Spark Team (Team 5) for COMSC 330 at Roger Williams University during the 2026 spring semester.
The goal for the application was to allow a professor to create a special topic's event, and then share it with students who are interested. The students are then able to choose which days on a given week they are available to attend. Finally, the professor who created the event will be able to navigate to the results page, which details what days had the most students available. 


The system was built as a full stack application, allowing the responses to be saved to a centralized database, and displayed within the frontend. The user interface was built using the JavaScript framework React, while the backend was constructed using a python library called fastAPI. The REST endpoints communicated with our database that uses MariaDB. Our team also chose to use Docker for its helpful Docker Compose feature that allowed us to containerize the database and allow for easy development across the team. 

Throughout this report we detail the full software development lifecycle, such as requirements, system design, implementation details, testing procedures, and our deployment considerations. Key design decisions such as our relational database schema, user experience choices, and development environments are documented. 

