= Introduction
The idea behind this project stemmed from the need to easily identify how many students are interested in a course, and when they are available to fit it into their schedules. While pre-existing solutions do exist, many of them require complex registration steps or offer far more functionality than is necessary for our shareholders use case. 

To address this need, we developed a lightweight scheduling tool that is tailored specifically for Roger Williams University, yet easily adapted to other course formats. The system displays the standard RWU time blocks, allowing a professor to easily select the slots they would like to offer. The professor can then take the sharable link generated by the application and distribute it to students however they see fit. The students can then simply indicate when they are available within a few clicks, and no need to create another hard to remember username and password.

The rest of this report goes through our requirements, how we designed and built the system, our testing, deployment steps, and what we learned from the whole experience. 

= Requirements 
The requirements for this project were simple. Create a software that allows professors to determine the best time to host a class based on the availability of prospective students. 

The software was prohibited from gathering data through external sources, such as Roger Central, the site in which students at RWU select their courses. 

In addition to the core functionality, it was a requirement that the user experience be straightforward. 

= Design & Implementation
Our website is composed of three separate entities: the React frontend, the FastAPI backend, and the MariaDB database. The frontend is what is displayed to the user. It allows the professor to input their own name as well as the course name to be displayed to the students. Professors are also able to specify which days they are willing to teach the course.

After the professor submits their choices they are provided with two URLs. The first one is to be provided to the students and leads to the student view where they will fill in availability. The second link is to be bookmarked by the professor in order to view the results after students have submitted their time preferences. On the results view they see a breakdown of how many students are available for each time slot. A colored heatmap is provided reflecting those counts. Both URLs are driven by a unique hash which is generated by the backend and stored within a table in the database.

On the student side, the user is given a similar block selection component which allows them to choose the days of which they are available to take the specified course. After the student creates their schedule they click submit and are met with a submission complete page. We specifically designed the software to check the browser’s local storage so that once a user submits they are not able to submit again.

The backend is what handles RESTful APIs as well as some of the application logic. When a student submits their availability it performs a POST request, and when results need to be displayed to the professor the backend handles a GET request. This report will get into more detail regarding these endpoints later on. 

For the database design we chose to use MariaDB since it is a relational database and would meet our requirements. In order to implement the database we leveraged the use of a docker-compose.yml document. This document allowed us to specify what our docker container would contain, such as MariaDB usernames, ports, and volumes.

