== How the Website Works 

- *Event Creation:* The professor creates a scheduling event through the backend. The system generates a unique hash for that event.
- *Distribution:* The professor shares the hashed URL with students.
- *Student Input:* Students visit the URL, enter their name, and click the time slots when they’re free. The UI supports clicking and dragging to select multiple slots at once.
- *Data Transmission:* Student availability is sent to the backend via a POST request and stored in the database.
- *Evaluation:* The professor visits the results endpoint to see which time slots have the most students available.


= Development Environment
During the construction of the project, there were many tools, languages, and libraries that each team member needed in order to run the project locally. To simplify the process of constructing the development environment, a document was created called overview.pdf. This document contained step-by-step instructions on installing required programs and packages, along with commands needed to run the project.

For the frontend, members were required to install the Node JavaScript runtime. To manage Node packages the program pnpm was used. On the backend, Python was required, with PIP being used for package management. The aforementioned overview.pdf listed the Python packages which required installation.

For the database, it was only necessary to have installed some version of Docker that was capable of running the Docker Compose command. By running that command, Docker created a MariaDB database locally on the computer. A seed.sql script was created that allowed Docker to insert mock tables into the database, preventing us from manually entering a schema.

During development, each member also was required to create their own .env file in order to configure needed environment variables such as the correct database credentials and ports. For version control we used Git since it allowed multiple branches to exist on the project. This meant that nobody was writing over someone else's code, and you could delegate tasks easier. The code and documentation was stored on GitHub.

As for the integrated development environments, each member of the team had their own preferences. All members shared the use of Microsoft Visual Studio Code when working on the frontend. When developing the backend and working with the database, Vim was used in conjunction with tmux.

= Target Environment
The target environment for this project is any device with a modern web browser. Since everything client-side is browser based there is no need for additional software installation.

= Testing
The majority of the testing was conducted manually by visiting the application’s pages and verifying that they worked as intended. For the professor view, this involved creating events, visiting the generated URLs, and browsing the results. For the student view, this involved selecting availability, submitting, and ensuring that a student could not submit to the same event twice. The browser console was used to view any errors that occurred during runtime.

For the backend, the FastAPI live documentation allowed us to test the GET and POST endpoints directly. Any automated unit testing was determined to be outside the scope of this project.

= Deployment
The system is designed for deployment either within the Roger Williams University LAN, or on a cloud platform. During demonstrations, the entire application was run on a laptop running a lightweight Linux operating system and connected to the University’s wireless network. 

= Summation and Conclusions
The team was able to successfully meet all core requirements such as class creations, availability submissions, and interest tracking. 
Key challenges that required overcoming were lack of knowledge on the technologies used, user interface clutter, and bridging the gap between frontend and backend data. 
Further improvements that can be worked on include allowing the option for selecting individual time slots as opposed to the typical M/W/F or T/Th. The ability for a professor to view which students are available on a given time slot is also a potential further implementation. 


